"Lin M., Fan K., Wang H.","Somali jet changes under the global warming",2008,"Acta Meteorologica Sinica","22","4",,"502","510",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-61349137509&partnerID=40&md5=5dd40036fd3e6b7f2ee2b89997a27aca","Nansen-Zhu International Research Center, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China; Graduate School, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100039, China","Lin, M., Nansen-Zhu International Research Center, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China, Graduate School, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100039, China; Fan, K., Nansen-Zhu International Research Center, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China; Wang, H., Nansen-Zhu International Research Center, Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Beijing 100029, China","Somali Jet changes will influence the variability of Asian monsoon and climate. How would Somali Jet changes respond to the global warming in the future climate? To address this question, we first evaluate the ability of IPCC-AR4 climate models and perform the 20th century climate in coupled models (20C3M) experiments to reproduce the observational features of the low level Somali Jet in JJA (June-July-August) for the period 1976-1999. Then, we project and discuss the changes of Somali Jet under the climate change of Scenario A2 (SRESA2) for the period 2005-2099. The results show that 18 IPCC-AR4 models have performed better in describing the climatological features of Somali Jet in the present climate simulations. Analysis of Somali Jet intensity changes from the multi-model ensemble results for the period 2005-2099 shows a weakened Somali Jet in the early 21st century (2010-2040), the strongest Somali Jet in the middle 21st century (2050-2060), as well as the weakest Somali Jet at the end of the 21st century (2070-2090). Compared with the period 1976-1999, the intensity of Somali Jet is weakening in general, and it becomes the weakest at the end of the 21st century. The results also suggest that the relationship between the intensity of Somali Jet in JJA and the increment of global mean surface air temperature is nonlinear, which is reflected differently among the models, suggesting the uncertainty of the IPCC-AR4 models. Considering the important role of Somali Jet in the Indian monsoon and East Asian monsoon and climate of China, the variability of Somali Jet and its evolvement under the present climate or future climate changes need to be further clarified.","Global warming; IPCC-AR4 models; Somali jet changes","air temperature; climate change; climate modeling; climate variation; global warming; jet; monsoon; twentieth century; twenty first century; Africa; Asia; China; East Africa; Eurasia; Far East; Somalia; Sub-Saharan Africa",,,,,,"Jing, C., Zhaoyong, G., Wang, L., Interannual (Interdecadal) variabilities of two cross-equatorial flows in association with the Asian summer monsoon variations (2007) Journal of Nanjing Institute of Meteorology, 30 (6), pp. 780-785. , in Chinese; Hui, G., Feng, X., Seasonal variation of the cross-equatorial flows and their influences on the onset of South China Sea summer monsoon (2006) Climatic and Environmental Research, 11 (1), pp. 57-68. , in Chinese; Gao, X., Zhao, Z., Ding, Y., Climate change due to greenhouse effects in China as simulated by a regional climate model. Part II: Climate change (2003) Acta Meteor. Sinica, 61 (1), pp. 29-38. , in Chinese; Hegerl, G., Meehl, G., Covery, C., Latif, M., McAvaney, B., Stouffer, R., 20C3M: CMIP collecting data from 20th century coupled model simulations (2003) CLIVAR exchange, pp. N0.26; Hori, M.E., Ueda, H., Impact of global warming on the East Asian winter monsoon as revealed by nine coupled atmosphere-ocean GCMS (2006) Geophys. Res. Lett, 33 (3), pp. L03713. , doi: 10.1029/2005GL024961; Jiang, D., Wang, H., Lang, X., Multimodel en